<h3>Elemental Maelstrom</h3>
<p>This is the first in a series of 2 Damage Over Time (DOT) spells magicians
receive.&nbsp; It's another good idea that was implemented in a way that
severely limits its usefulness.&nbsp; This spell does 250 damage instantly and
then 350 more damage over 30 seconds.&nbsp; It also pushes the target back one
foot, which interrupts casting.&nbsp; It costs 240 mana.&nbsp; At this level,
you also get Shock of Swords, which does 580 - 600 damage instantly for 250
damage.&nbsp; SoS does not push back the target.&nbsp; Both spells check against
magic.</p>
<p>At 44, Elemental Maelstrom is a bit more efficient since Shock of Swords will
max at 580 damage.&nbsp; However, it does that damage more slowly.&nbsp; That
means your group (or your pet) will need to fight longer -- taking more damage
as well.&nbsp; The push back of EM is nice (conjuration-based shock spells have
a knockback of 0.5 whereas EM has a knockback of 1), but since the spell is slow casting,
it cannot be relied on as a stun to interrupt a gating or healing mob.</p>
<p>Why use it?</p>
<p>I've seen magicians post that this spell is resisted less than SoS.&nbsp; I
haven't seen evidence of that.&nbsp; However, from an analysis of the spell data
file, EM should be resisted a bit less than SoS.&nbsp; Tech note: As of July
2002, SoS has a resist modifier of 5 whereas EM has a resist modifier of 0.</p>
<p> I've seen magicians post that this spell
generates less aggro.&nbsp; I haven't seen evidence of that -- although it does
follow that the aggro is spread out over more time.&nbsp; If you like to nuke at
the beginning of the fight, you may find that opening with EM and then casting
SoS generates less initial aggro than 2 casts of SoS.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
<p> Note: I do not recommend nuking twice at the beginning of a fight unless you
are trying to move the mob toward you.&nbsp; (There are times when that makes
perfect sense!)</p>
<p>I've also seen many magicians state that this spell is great for doing more
damage in a short period of time [than could be done with other spells].&nbsp;
That just doesn't make sense.&nbsp; This DOT is slower than our DD -- both in
terms of casting and in terms of delivering the damage.&nbsp; Yes, you can cast
this DOT and then a DD while the DOT is still &quot;working&quot; -- but if
you'd cast 2 DD, you'd have done the same damage in less time.&nbsp; Mages
cannot summon a focus item that works on DOTs, making EM even less
attractive.&nbsp; (There are dropped items in the game that have the effect
Extended Affliction which benefit DOTs).</p>
<p>If you haven't figured it out by now, my opinion of EM is that with the
exception of the knockback, it was not implemented in a useful fashion.</p>
<p>This spell is a Velious era, drop-only spell.&nbsp; It's fairly common.</p>

<h3>Modulating Rod</h3>

<p>The Modulating Rod is one of the class-defining spells for magicians.&nbsp;
This spell summons a 1HB weapon of fair stats.&nbsp; However, the weapon is
rarely used as a weapon.&nbsp; It's the effect that makes it such a desired
item.&nbsp; The rod has a single charge of modulation.&nbsp; The effect (just
right click it, you do not need to equip it) instantly converts 225 HP into 150
mana.&nbsp; The rod vanishes upon use.</p>

<p>Since the rod costs 200 mana to make and is lore, it isn't a way for you to
make mana batteries for yourself.&nbsp; It's used primarily as a tool for
assisting with mass resurrections and healing in raid-level encounters.&nbsp;</p>

<p>It's a good idea to make sure that you have one in your inventory at all
times.&nbsp; It's also good practice to make sure that your group's healers and
casters have one in their inventories as well.&nbsp; You never know when 225 HP
for 150 mana would turn the course of a battle.</p>

<p>To summon a rod, you must target a player.&nbsp; The rod will appear on the
player's cursor.</p>

<p>Note: Summoning a rod is a beneficial spell.&nbsp; If you summon a rod during
combat, you will take a faction hit!</p>

<p><i>Historical Note: Rods were once tradable.&nbsp; In that day, many newbies
died as evil mages gave them rods.&nbsp; Many more beggars died, as their greed
got them killed by &quot;phat loot&quot; they begged from a mage.&nbsp; But VI
ended all of that.&nbsp; Rods are no longer useable by players whose max health
is less than 225 hp.&nbsp; On a bright note, high level players occasionally
kill themselves with a rod because their current health was less than 225 when
the rod was used.</i></p>

<h3>Upgrade your Healing</h3>

<p>Refresh Summoning, a 338 point heal is waiting for you in the Plane of
Knowledge.&nbsp; This spell will scale a bit as you level.&nbsp; If you cast it
at level 65, it will heal 380 points.&nbsp; Like all pet heals, it cures 10
disease counters on the pet as well.</p>

